Methods
Study design and participants
The REWIND trial is an international, multicentre, 
randomised, double-blind placebo-controlled trial at 
371 sites in 24 countries.8 Adults (aged ≥50 years) with 
either established or newly diagnosed type 2 diabetes and 
additional cardiovascular risk factors were recruited if they 
had glycated haemoglobin (HbA1c) of 9·5% (80 mmol/mol) 
or lower on up to two oral glucose-lowering drugs with or 
without basal insulin and a body-mass index of at least 
23 kg/m². A further inclusion criterion was previous 
myocardial infarction, ischaemic stroke, revas­cular­isa­tion, 
unstable angina requiring hospital admiss­ion, or image-
proven myocardial ischaemia. For those individuals aged 
55 years or older, an additional inclusion criterion was 
myo­car­dial ischaemia, imaging evidence of atherosclerosis, 
hyper­tension with left ventricular hyper­trophy, or renal 
disease (defined as persistent albumin­uria or an estimated 
glom­erular filtration rate [eGFR] <60 mL/min per 1·73 m²). 
For individuals aged 60 years or older, a further inclusion 
criterion was to have at least two cardio­vascular risk factors.
Key exclusion criteria were a coronary or cerebrovascular 
event within the previous 2 months, plans for revascular­
isation, severe hypoglycaemia in the previous year, eGFR 
less than 15 mL/min per 1·73 m², cancer in the previous 
5 years, or a life expectancy of less than 1 year. Full 
inclusion and exclusion criteria have been published.8
The REWIND trial was approved by research ethics 
boards at all study sites. All participants provided written 
informed consent. An independent data monitoring 
committee (appendix p 2) carefully monitored the trial and 
reviewed accruing and unmasked main trial data every 
6 months. The committee did not monitor cognitive data.
Randomisation and masking
Before randomisation, all participants entered a 3-week, 
single-­blind run­-in period, during which time they 
received placebo and were taught how to inject the 
study drug. Participants who were taking a dipeptidyl 
peptidase 4 (DPP4) inhibitor or GLP­1 receptor agonist at 
screening discontinued these drugs at the start of the 
run-­in period. Otherwise, they were instructed to remain 
on their usual antihyperglycaemic treatment.
Participants who were 100% adherent to placebo injec­
tions every week during the single-blind run-in period and 
who still met eligibility criteria were randomly assigned 
subcutaneous injections every week of either dulaglutide 
(1·5 mg) or an equal volume of identically appearing 
placebo. Randomisation was done by the sponsor using 
a computer-generated code with stratifi­cation by site. Par­
ticipants and all study and sponsor personnel were masked 
to treatment allocation until the database was locked.
Procedures
Individuals in both study groups were instructed to inject 
study drug on the same day at around the same time every 
week. We followed up participants at least every 6 months 
for the REWIND trial’s composite primary outcome of 
non-fatal stroke, non-fatal myocardial infarction, or death 
from cardiovascular or unknown causes.
The REWIND protocol included prespecified assess­
ments of cognitive status at baseline and at the 2-year, 
5-year, and end-of-study visit, which was up to 8 years after 
initiation. We administered two validated meas­ures of cog­
ni­tive status: the Montreal Cognitive Assessment (MoCA) 
test and the Digit Symbol Substitution Test (DSST).
MoCA is a cognitive screening test that has been validated 
in the setting of mild cognitive impairment and sub­
sequently adopted in many clinical settings. The test 
comprises a 1-page 30-item questionnaire, which was 
designed to be administered over a period of approximately 
10 min in the participant’s first language using a vali­dated 
translation. MoCA assesses seven cognitive domains, com­
prising short-term memory, visuospatial abilities, exec­u­tive 
Research in context
Evidence before this study
We searched PubMed for reports of randomised, double-blind, 
placebo-controlled trials published in English between 
Jan 1, 2010, and Jan 31, 2020, in which the effect of 
glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) receptor agonists on cognitive 
status was assessed. We used the search terms “GLP-1-RA”, 
“glucagon-like peptide receptor 1 agonist”, glucagon-like 
peptide receptor 1 analog”, “lixisenatide”, “liraglutide”, 
“semaglutide”, “taspoglutide”, “albiglutide”, “dulaglutide”, 
“cognition”, “cognitive dysfunction”, “dementia”, 
“Alzheimer’s”, and “randomised”. Our search identified 
two placebo-controlled trials of liraglutide in which 38 and 
41 participants were studied for 26 and 12 weeks, respectively, 
and another trial of exenatide in which 18 participants were 
studied for 18 months. None of the trials reported cognitive 
improvements in people with diabetes.
Added value of this study
To our knowledge, our report is the first to report some 
evidence for reduced cognitive impairment with a GLP-1 
receptor agonist in a large long-term trial. Although 
exploratory, these findings with dulaglutide suggest that this 
agent, and other GLP-1 receptor agonists, might have cognitive 
benefits in people with diabetes.
Implications of all the available evidence
GLP-1 receptor agonists might reduce cognitive impairment in 
people with type 2 diabetes and additional cardiovascular risk 
factors. The ageing population and high projected rates of 
cognitive impairment support the need for randomised trials of 
these agents with prespecified cognitive measures to extend 
and better elucidate their cognitive effects.
