function, attention, concentration, working memory, and 
language.10 The score on MoCA is equal to the number of 
items out of 30 answered correctly, plus one extra point if 
the individual reports 12 years or fewer of educa­tion. 
Controlled validation studies in cognitively normal indivi­
duals have reported a mean MoCA score of 27·4 (SD 2·2). 
However, population-based studies of presumably cog­
nitively intact people report much lower mean scores.11
DSST is a subtest of the Wechsler Adult Intelligence 
Scale (third edition) and assesses a wide array of cognitive 
domains, including visual-motor speed and coordina­tion, 
capacity for learning, attention, concen­tration, and short-
term memory.12 DSST consists of rows of nine randomly 
ordered symbols with a blank square under­neath and a key 
at the top of the page that pairs each symbol to a number. 
Respondents fill the blank space under each symbol with 
the corresponding number as quickly as possible over a 
period of 2 min. The score on DSST is the number of 
consecutive digit–symbol pairs correctly completed within 
2 min, and the maxi­mum possible score is 135. DSST 
has been extensively used to measure cognitive function 
in cognitively intact individuals with and without type 2 
diabetes. Validation studies have shown that DSST predicts 
future cogni­tive dysfunction and disability; is relatively 
easy to administer; is not language specific; and the 
score correlates with measures of physical function and 
future cognitive decline.13 When DSST was used in ran­
domised controlled trials of cogni­tively intact people 
with dysglycaemia, mean baseline scores ranged from 
3614 to 52.15
During the REWIND trial, MoCA scores provided by 
study sites were all centrally reviewed at the Population 
Health Research Institute (McMaster University, Hamilton, 
ON, Canada) by TC-Y, HCG, and statisticians who were 
unaware of the random allocation. Items that were left 
unchecked were assigned a score of 0 and items that were 
graded above the maximum possible score were assigned 
the maximum score. The sum of this revised score for 
every participant was used for all MoCA analyses. Copies of 
DSST were not sent centrally, thus, scores on DSST used 
for all analy­ses were those provided by study sites on 
the case report form, after on-site test scoring by the 
research assistants.
Before unmasking, we made the decision to convert 
every individual’s raw MoCA and DSST scores to country-
standardised scores, to account for evidence that the 
normal range of cognitive test scores might differ by 
country11,16 because of regional or cultural differences. This 
conversion was done by first calculating the baseline 
mean and SD of the MoCA and DSST score within every 
country. These baseline means and SDs were then used to 
calculate a standardised MoCA and DSST score for every 
participant at every timepoint, by subtracting the country-
specific baseline mean raw score from the individual’s raw 
score at that timepoint and dividing the difference by the 
country-specific baseline SD. Thus, within every country, 
the mean (SD) of all participants’ baseline standardised 
scores for both the MoCA and DSST was 0 (1).
Outcomes
The primary outcome of the REWIND trial was first 
occurrence of non-fatal myocardial infarction, non-fatal 
stroke, or death from cardiovascular or unknown causes, 
which has been reported.8 Secondary outcomes were a 
com­posite microvascular outcome comprising diabetic 
retinopathy or renal disease, hospital admission for 
unstable angina, each component of the primary com­
posite outcome, death, and heart failure requiring either 
hospital admission or an urgent visit; these have also 
been reported.8
The exploratory primary cognitive outcome we report 
here was country-standardised substantive cognitive 
impair­ment (SCI), defined as the first occurrence of a 
post-randomisation country-standardised MoCA or DSST 
score of –1·5 SD or less (ie, more than 1·5 SDs below 
the mean baseline score). The 1·5 SD threshold was 
