as continuous variables.
Statistical analysis
The sample size for the REWIND trial was based on an 
estimated primary outcome incidence of 2% per year 
in the placebo group, a two-sided significance level 
of 5%, a 3-year recruitment period, an annual dropout 
rate of 0·15%, follow-up for a maximum of 8 years, and 
90% power to detect a hazard ratio (HR) of less than 0·82 
for the primary outcome. No sample size calculations 
were done for the exploratory cognitive analyses.
All analyses were done using an intention-to-treat 
approach and were restricted to participants who had a 
baseline MoCA or DSST score and at least one follow-up 
score of the same type. We summarised continuous 
variables as mean (SD) and binary variables as number 
(%). We used Cox proportional-hazard models to estimate 
the hazard of SCI and SCI-based composite outcomes 
with dulaglutide versus placebo, both before and after 
account­ing for every individual’s baseline standardised 
MoCA and DSST scores. Sensitivity of the Cox model to 
the discrete nature of the results (ie, because of the 
intermittent administration of the cognitive tests) was 
assessed by repeating the main analyses using a dis­
crete time pro­portional odds logistic model. Differences 
for effects within exploratory subgroups defined by age, 
sex, educa­tion, previous cardiovascular disease, previous 
stroke or TIA, HbA1c, albumin:creatinine ratio (ACR), 
eGFR, and baseline MoCA and DSST scores were 
analysed by includ­ing the subgroup and a subgroup–
treatment interac­tion term in the model. We also used 
Cox proportional-hazard models to estimate the univari­
able and multivariable relation between risk factors for 
cognitive impairment (ie, those that were also used for the 
subgroup analyses), and between random assignment to 
dulaglutide (after adjustment for predictor variables with a 
significant HR) and the first occurrence of the cognitive 
outcome. Finally, repeated measures linear mixed-effects 
models estimated the effect of dulaglutide on the least 
squares mean difference in the standardised MoCA and 
DSST scores, with the standardised base­line scores as 
covariates, participant as a random effect, and fixed effects 
for treatment, visit, and treatment–visit interaction.18
All reported p values are two-sided, and a nominal level 
of significance of 0·05 was used, with no adjustments for 
