The REWIND trial is registered with ClinicalTrials.gov, 
NCT01394952.
Role of the funding source
The REWIND trial was sponsored and funded by Eli Lilly 
and Company and led by an international steering com­
mittee that was coordinated by the Population Health 
Research Institute (Hamilton, ON, Canada), which also 
analysed the data for this report after the database was 
locked. ICON Clinical Research managed study sites and 
obtained data. Scientists employed by the funder were on 
the REWIND steering committee and contributed to trial 
design, trial implementation, and data interpretation. All 
authors and the sponsor jointly made the decision to 
submit for publication. The corresponding author had 
full access to all data in the study and had final 
responsibility for the decision to submit for publication.
Results
Between Aug 18, 2011, and Aug 14, 2013, 12 133 patients 
were screened for the REWIND trial, of whom 
10 917 began the 3-week run-in period. 9901 (91%) of those 
who began the run-in period were randomly assigned 
subcutaneous injections every week of either dulaglutide 
(n=4949) or an equal volume of placebo (n=4952).
Follow-up ended on Aug 21, 2018; median follow-up 
was 5·4 (IQR 5·1–5·9) years. Baseline and at least one 
follow-up MoCA or DSST test result were available for 
8828 (89%) of 9901 participants, of whom 4456 were 
assigned dulaglutide and 4372 were assigned placebo. 
Compared with the 1073 (11%) individuals with incom­
plete data, the 8828 participants included in the explor­
atory cognitive analysis were younger, had a shorter 
dura­tion of diabetes, were more likely to be of white 
ethnic origin, had a shorter duration of education, had 
a lower prevalence of pre­vious cardiovascular disease, 
cerebrovascular disease, and albuminuria, were heavier, 
and had a lower systolic blood pressure, lower HbA1c, and 
a higher eGFR (appendix p 3).
Baseline characteristics by treatment group are pre­sented 
in table 1. The mean age of the 8828 participants was 
