561 (6%) had atrial fibrillation. Concomitant drug use at the 
final study visit is shown in the appendix (p 4). Dulaglutide 
was well tolerated, with no differences from placebo with 
respect to serious or expected adverse events.8
The incidence of the primary cognitive outcome 
(country-standardised SCI) in participants assigned 
dulaglutide was 4·05 per 100 patient-years, and in those 
assigned placebo it was 4·35 per 100 patient-years 
(HR 0·93, 95% CI 0·85–1·02; p=0·11). After scrutinising 
the effect of dulaglutide on country-standardised SCI in 
subgroups defined according to thirds of the baseline 
MoCA and DSST scores (table 2; appendix p 7), a greater 
effect was seen in participants with the lowest baseline 
scores (pinteraction=0·0043 for MoCA; pinteraction=0·028 for 
DSST), highlighting the relevance of an individual’s 
baseline score. All subsequent analyses were, therefore, 
adjusted for every individual’s baseline MoCA and DSST 
scores.
After post-hoc adjustment for baseline MoCA and DSST 
standardised scores, participants assigned dulaglutide 
had a 14% lower hazard of baseline score adjusted SCI 
than did those assigned placebo (HR 0·86, 95% CI 
0·79–0·95; p=0·0018; figure 1; appendix p 8). When the 
analysis was repeated using a discrete time proportional 
odds logistic model, the odds ratio was 0·87 (95% CI 
0·78–0·96; p=0·0050). Similar estimates of effect were 
noted after additional adjustment for age, sex, education, 
or ethnicity, and after including SCI within various com­
posite outc­omes, including stroke (figure 1). Adjusting 
for first incident stroke (as a time-varying covariate) 
before the cognitive outcome occurred did not affect the 
result (adjusted HR 0·86, 95% CI 0·78–0·94; p=0·0008). 
Finally, similar treatment effects on country-standardised 
SCI were also noted across subgroups defined on the 
basis of age, education, previous cardio­vascular dis­
ease, previous stroke or TIA, baseline MoCA or DSST 
score, HbA1c, the natural logarithm of ACR, and eGFR 
(pinteraction>0·07 for all; figure 2). A signi­ficant interaction 
was noted with respect to men versus women (p=0·032; 
figure 2).
Table 3 shows the effect of dulaglutide on mean country-
standardised MoCA and DSST scores (appendix p 9). 
During follow-up, the mean country-standardised MoCA 
score was –0·055 (SE 0·013) in participants assigned 
dulaglutide and –0·074 (0·013) in those assigned placebo, 
with an overall baseline score adjusted between-group 
difference of 0·019 units (95% CI –0·018 to 0·056; 
p=0·32). The mean country-standardised DSST score 
was –0·170 (SE 0·010) in the dulaglutide group and 
–0·189 (SE 0·010) in the placebo group, with an overall 
base­line score adjusted between-group difference of 
0·019 units (95% CI –0·008 to 0·045; p=0·17). When these 
analyses were restricted to participants whose baseline 
MoCA or DSST scores were in the lowest third, no 
differences between treatments were noted (appendix p 5). 
Adjustment for sex did not alter the results.
To support the definition of SCI that was used in these 
analyses (ie, a post-randomisation country-standardised 
MoCA or DSST score of ≤–1·5 SDs, adjusted for baseline 
standardised scores), epidemiological cohort analyses of 
all participants were done to estimate the hazard of SCI 
in the presence of various known risk factors for cognitive 
impairment. The univariable hazard of SCI was signi­
ficantly higher in people older than 70 years versus those 
aged 70 years or younger, in women versus men, in 
participants with 12 years of education or less versus 
those with a longer period of education, in individuals 
with a previous stroke or TIA versus neither, in people 
