with a low versus high baseline MoCA or DSST score, in 
those with HbA1c greater than 8·1% (ie, the highest 
quartile) versus 8·1 % or lower, and people with more 
versus less albuminuria (defined by ACR; appendix p 6). 
After adjustment for univariable predictor variables with 
a significant HR, the hazard of dulaglutide for country-
standardised SCI (adjusted for the two baseline cognitive 
tests) was 0·89 (95% CI 0·81–0·97; p=0·012). 
Discussion
The findings of our exploratory analysis provide some 
evidence to show that after approximately 5 years of 
treatment with dulaglutide injections every week, the 
hazard of country-standardised SCI (adjusted for baseline 
score) might be reduced by 14% compared with placebo in 
people aged 50 years or older with type 2 diabetes. 
Furthermore, the effect of the inter­vention was consistent 
across different baseline character­istics and persisted after 
accounting for baseline variations in age, education, and 
ethnic origin.
Country-standardised SCI adjusted for baseline score 
represents a novel way of analysing changes in cognitive 
test scores over time. Although country-standardised 
scores and the 1·5 SD threshold for this categorical 
cognitive outcome were prespecified before unmasking, 
adjustment for every individual’s baseline standardised 
scores was included afterwards, based on evidence of a 
differential effect of the intervention across thirds of the 
baseline score in the current study and to control for 
random differences between baseline scores.19 The 
observation that several known risk factors significantly 
predicted this adjusted outcome in epidemiological 
analyses of the REWIND data (appendix p 6) supports its 
use as a measure of cognitive impairment.
The finding that dulaglutide reduced cognitive impair­
ment in this large long-term trial is consistent with reports 
from small short-term studies in which a beneficial effect 
of GLP-1 receptor agonists on cognitive function was 
suggested. For example, in a trial of 38 individuals with 
Alzheimer’s disease who were randomly assigned a 
26-week course of either liraglutide or placebo, liraglutide 
reduced the decline in brain glucose con­sumption.20 In 
another study, 4 weeks of treatment with liraglutide 
improved cognitive test scores in 19 individuals with 
mood disorders and impaired executive function.21 Finally, 
in a study of 45 individuals with Parkinson’s disease, 
12 months of treatment with exenatide improved both 
motor symptoms and cognitive test scores.22 
Since stroke is associated with cognitive dysfunction,4 
the possibility was investigated that these findings might 
be a manifestation of a previously reported 24% reduction 
in the hazard of a clinically apparent stroke.8 The HR was 
unaffected by adjusting for incident clinical stroke, which 
suggests that the reduced risk of clinical stroke cannot 
statistically account for the observations. However, this 
finding does not rule out the possibility that an unmeas­
ured benefit on subclinical or silent strokes could be 
playing a part. Alternatively, these findings could reflect a 
neuroprotective effect of dulaglutide that is directly or 
indirectly mediated through the GLP-1 receptor. This 
receptor is found in many brain areas related to memory 
and learning, including the dentate gyrus, hippocampus, 
and cerebral cortex, as well as on glial cells.23,24 GLP-1 
receptor knockout mice show impaired learning and 
memory that is reversed after gene transfer of the receptor, 
while overexpression of hippocampal GLP-1 receptors in 
rats improves learning and memory.25 Moreover, genetic 
loci related to DPP4, which has a role in GLP-1 inactivation, 
are independently associated with hippocampal volume.26 
Finally, GLP-1 agonists stimulate neurite outgrowth in cell 
cultures.27 Postulated explanations for these effects include 
reduced neuronal apoptosis, astrogliosis, protection of 
synapse and neurons from amyloid β and oxidative 
toxicity, enhancement of neuroplasticity, and reduction 
of inflammation.28,29
Dulaglutide did not affect MoCA and DSST scores over 
time when analysed as continuous variables. This finding 
is probably attributable to the wide variability noted in 
baseline test scores, unmeasured between-participant 
and within-participant differences in the way the test was 
administered at various times, and differences in the 
effect of the intervention in people with higher versus 
lower baseline scores. The noise introduced by these 
effects could have obscured the signal that was apparent 
in the categorical outcome that focused on big effects 
only and that controlled for both country (and therefore 
culture) and baseline scores.
The strengths of our study are the long duration of 
follow-up, the large sample size, the international multi­
country setting, and that our study is part of a randomised 
trial that controlled for variations in how the MoCA and 
DSST tests were administered and interpreted. Our 
study also included a novel cognitive measure based on 
two cognitive tests that accounted for regional vari­
ations in test scores and the individual’s baseline test 
score. Our study is limited by its exploratory nature, the 
2-year time interval between the baseline and first 
subsequent test, and the fact that the additional adjust­
ment of the SCI outcome for every individual’s baseline 
standardised test scores was not prespecified before 
unmasking. Furthermore, only two cognitive tests were 
administered at baseline in a wide variety of settings and 
cultures (with no replication to minimise random vari­
ability), the absence of any ante­cedent measures of 
cognitive status (to assess prerandom­isation cognitive 
trajectory), the absence of any data relat­ing the change in 
the hazard of this cognitive outcome to future clinically 
important cognitive states such as dementia, and the 
possibility that the two cognitive tests might not have 
assessed all cognitive domains affected by dia­betes. 
Future postrandomisation analyses might investigate 
the relation between dulaglutide-mediated changes in 
glucose, systolic blood pressure, or weight and these cog­
nitive outcomes.
Articles
www.thelancet.com/neurology   Vol 19   July 2020	
589
In conclusion, the findings of our exploratory analy­
sis suggest that dulaglutide could reduce cognitive impair­
ment in people aged 50 years or older with type 2 diabetes. 
In view of the emerging evidence that dulaglutide8 and 
some other GLP-1 receptor agonists30 reduce cardiovascular 
events, and might have a particular beneficial effect on 
stroke,9 our findings support the need for dedicated 
studies of the effect of GLP-1 receptor agonists such as 
dulaglutide on brain health and cognitive function.
